04078nam a22005895i 9780228010074DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280100747 a10.1515/97802280100742doi  a(DE-B1597)656302  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBR759b.R35 2021 7aREL1080202bisacsh04a274.22231 aReagles, David G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSearching for God in Britain and Beyond :bReading Letters to Malcolm Muggeridge, 1966–1982 /cDavid G. Reagles. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tReading and Writing as Self-Discovery -- tRecalibrating Religious Authority -- tReading Religious Decline -- tReading for Social Engagement -- tReading Muggeridge in Plural Societies -- tConclusion -- tEditions of Malcolm Muggeridge’s Books, circa 1969–90 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen writer and media personality Malcolm Muggeridge unexpectedly converted to Christianity in the 1960s, fans around the world flocked to his devotional writings and television programs about his spiritual journey. Because Muggeridge was critical of institutional Christianity and initially refused to join a church, he inspired a special affinity in those who were disillusioned with mainstream religious authority. Readers from around the world sent him deeply personal letters describing their spiritual and religious lives, revealing their anxieties, doubts, and hopes about the future of Christianity.In Searching for God in Britain and Beyond David Reagles draws on nearly two thousand of these remarkable fan letters to explore the thoughts and feelings of ordinary Christians in a time of cultural and religious upheaval. In these candid letters, Muggeridge’s correspondents wrestled with their experiences of faith and doubt, the value of institutional religion, uncertainties about permissiveness in society, the proper role of Christian social activism, and the forces of secularism. For these fans and skeptics alike, reading and writing were a vital means of working out their religious identities and convictions amid the supposed decline of Christendom.Searching for God in Britain and Beyond provides a rare and fascinating glimpse into the inner worlds of ordinary Christians in the 1960s and 1970s, revealing how the secularization of postwar society felt to average people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAuthors and readerszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aChristian lifezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aChristianszGreat BritainvCorrespondence. 7aRELIGION / Christian Church / History.2bisacsh  aSecularization.  abook.  aemotional practices.  aemotions.  afan mail.  ahistory.  aletter writing.  along 1970s.  areading.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801007440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228010074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228010074/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles